const Q_ENGLISH_2007=[{"id": "objective>English>2007>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p> <br/>   <br/> PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> It is of no more use to give advise to the idle than to pour water into a sieve, but it strikes me that lazy people ought to have a large looking glass hung up where they are bound to see themselves in it.  If their eyes are at all like mine, they will never bear to look at themselves long or often. The ugliest sight in world is one of those through-bred loafers, who would hardly hold up his basin if it were to rain with porridge; and certain, would never hold up a bigger pot than he wanted filled fore himself. <br/>  <br/> Perhaps, if the shower should turn to beer, he might wake himself up a bit, but he would make up for it afterwards, since as a slothful man. He folds his hand in sleep and hates to get up even for his meals. Men like him ought to be treated like the drone which the bees drive out of their hives for inactivity and overdependence. Every man ought to have patience and pity for poverty; but for laziness, a long whip might be better. This would be a healthy treatment for all sluggards, but there is no chance of some of them getting their full dose of this medicine, for they were born with silver spoon in their mouths, and like spoons will scarce stir their own tea unless somebody lends them a hand. They are like the proverbial dog that leaned his head against the wall to bark and, like lazy sheep, it is too much trouble for them their eyes if the glass were hung for them.  <br/>  <br/> If I seem to hit hard at the sluggards, it is because I know they can bear it, for if they were seed on the threshing floor, you would thresh many days to get them out of the straw, for laziness is in their bones, and will show itself in their idle flesh, no matter what you do with them. <br/>  <br/> Which of the following explains the point being made in the second paragraph?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The drone and the slothful often look themselves up in the mirror</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The drone and the slothful are idle so they depend on others for their needs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The drone and the sluggards are lazy people who sleeps a lot</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The drone and the slothful hover around</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The drone and the slothful are idle so they depend on others for their needs. This is a summary of the 2nd paragraph.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p> <br/>   <br/> PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> It is of no more use to give advise to the idle than to pour water into a sieve, but it strikes me that lazy people ought to have a large looking glass hung up where they are bound to see themselves in it.  If their eyes are at all like mine, they will never bear to look at themselves long or often. The ugliest sight in world is one of those through-bred loafers, who would hardly hold up his basin if it were to rain with porridge; and certain, would never hold up a bigger pot than he wanted filled fore himself. <br/>  <br/> Perhaps, if the shower should turn to beer, he might wake himself up a bit, but he would make up for it afterwards, since as a slothful man. He folds his hand in sleep and hates to get up even for his meals. Men like him ought to be treated like the drone which the bees drive out of their hives for inactivity and overdependence. Every man ought to have patience and pity for poverty; but for laziness, a long whip might be better. This would be a healthy treatment for all sluggards, but there is no chance of some of them getting their full dose of this medicine, for they were born with silver spoon in their mouths, and like spoons will scarce stir their own tea unless somebody lends them a hand. They are like the proverbial dog that leaned his head against the wall to bark and, like lazy sheep, it is too much trouble for them their eyes if the glass were hung for them.  <br/>  <br/> If I seem to hit hard at the sluggards, it is because I know they can bear it, for if they were seed on the threshing floor, you would thresh many days to get them out of the straw, for laziness is in their bones, and will show itself in their idle flesh, no matter what you do with them. <br/> Which of the following represents the author's view in the passage?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The slothful will not get out of bed unless someone wakes them up</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Laziness leads to poverty so both should be rejected with equal vehemence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Idle and unproductive people should have no place in society </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Loafers carry their basins about looking for who to fill them with food </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The author's view in the passage is that idle and unproductive people should have no place in society. This is evident from the author's comparison of lazy people to drones that bees drive out of their hives for inactivity and overdependence. The author also suggests that a long whip might be a better treatment for laziness, indicating a strong disapproval of such behavior.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p> <br/>   <br/> PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> It is of no more use to give advise to the idle than to pour water into a sieve, but it strikes me that lazy people ought to have a large looking glass hung up where they are bound to see themselves in it.  If their eyes are at all like mine, they will never bear to look at themselves long or often. The ugliest sight in world is one of those through-bred loafers, who would hardly hold up his basin if it were to rain with porridge; and certain, would never hold up a bigger pot than he wanted filled fore himself. <br/>  <br/> Perhaps, if the shower should turn to beer, he might wake himself up a bit, but he would make up for it afterwards, since as a slothful man. He folds his hand in sleep and hates to get up even for his meals. Men like him ought to be treated like the drone which the bees drive out of their hives for inactivity and overdependence. Every man ought to have patience and pity for poverty; but for laziness, a long whip might be better. This would be a healthy treatment for all sluggards, but there is no chance of some of them getting their full dose of this medicine, for they were born with silver spoon in their mouths, and like spoons will scarce stir their own tea unless somebody lends them a hand. They are like the proverbial dog that leaned his head against the wall to bark and, like lazy sheep, it is too much trouble for them their eyes if the glass were hung for them.  <br/>  <br/> If I seem to hit hard at the sluggards, it is because I know they can bear it, for if they were seed on the threshing floor, you would thresh many days to get them out of the straw, for laziness is in their bones, and will show itself in their idle flesh, no matter what you do with them. <br/> One conclusion that can be drawn from the opening paragraph is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it is a waste of time to advise a lazy man because he will always use a sieve to sit the advice </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lazy people are thorough-bred loafers who cannot even eat their porridge</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">though lazy people have ugly faces, they like to see themselves in the mirror</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lazy people work only to satisfy their own immediate needs</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The conclusion that can be drawn from the opening paragraph is that lazy people work only to satisfy their own immediate needs. This is evident from the author's description of a lazy person who would hardly hold up his basin if it were to rain with porridge and certainly would never hold up a bigger pot than he wanted filled for himself. This suggests that lazy people are only concerned with their own immediate needs and not with contributing to society or helping others.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p> <br/>   <br/> PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> It is of no more use to give advise to the idle than to pour water into a sieve, but it strikes me that lazy people ought to have a large looking glass hung up where they are bound to see themselves in it.  If their eyes are at all like mine, they will never bear to look at themselves long or often. The ugliest sight in world is one of those through-bred loafers, who would hardly hold up his basin if it were to rain with porridge; and certain, would never hold up a bigger pot than he wanted filled fore himself. <br/>  <br/> Perhaps, if the shower should turn to beer, he might wake himself up a bit, but he would make up for it afterwards, since as a slothful man. He folds his hand in sleep and hates to get up even for his meals. Men like him ought to be treated like the drone which the bees drive out of their hives for inactivity and overdependence. Every man ought to have patience and pity for poverty; but for laziness, a long whip might be better. This would be a healthy treatment for all sluggards, but there is no chance of some of them getting their full dose of this medicine, for they were born with silver spoon in their mouths, and like spoons will scarce stir their own tea unless somebody lends them a hand. They are like the proverbial dog that leaned his head against the wall to bark and, like lazy sheep, it is too much trouble for them their eyes if the glass were hung for them.  <br/>  <br/> If I seem to hit hard at the sluggards, it is because I know they can bear it, for if they were seed on the threshing floor, you would thresh many days to get them out of the straw, for laziness is in their bones, and will show itself in their idle flesh, no matter what you do with them. <br/> The expression <em>if the shower should turn to beer, he might wake himself up a bit suggests that lazy people</em></div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are gourmets</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are pleasure-loving </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have been showers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are inconsiderate</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'if the shower should turn to beer, he might wake himself up a bit' suggests that lazy people might be more inclined to take action if there is a reward or pleasure involved. This aligns with the option 'are pleasure-loving'. The phrase is a metaphorical way of saying that lazy people might be more motivated to do something if there is an immediate gratification or reward involved, in this case, the pleasure of drinking beer.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p> <br/>   <br/> PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> It is of no more use to give advise to the idle than to pour water into a sieve, but it strikes me that lazy people ought to have a large looking glass hung up where they are bound to see themselves in it.  If their eyes are at all like mine, they will never bear to look at themselves long or often. The ugliest sight in world is one of those through-bred loafers, who would hardly hold up his basin if it were to rain with porridge; and certain, would never hold up a bigger pot than he wanted filled fore himself. <br/>  <br/> Perhaps, if the shower should turn to beer, he might wake himself up a bit, but he would make up for it afterwards, since as a slothful man. He folds his hand in sleep and hates to get up even for his meals. Men like him ought to be treated like the drone which the bees drive out of their hives for inactivity and overdependence. Every man ought to have patience and pity for poverty; but for laziness, a long whip might be better. This would be a healthy treatment for all sluggards, but there is no chance of some of them getting their full dose of this medicine, for they were born with silver spoon in their mouths, and like spoons will scarce stir their own tea unless somebody lends them a hand. They are like the proverbial dog that leaned his head against the wall to bark and, like lazy sheep, it is too much trouble for them their eyes if the glass were hung for them.  <br/>  <br/> If I seem to hit hard at the sluggards, it is because I know they can bear it, for if they were seed on the threshing floor, you would thresh many days to get them out of the straw, for laziness is in their bones, and will show itself in their idle flesh, no matter what you do with them. <br/> From the argument in the last paragraph, it can be concluded that the sluggards are</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">phlegmatic when advised </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">weary of sound advice </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">impervious to advice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">intolerant of good advice</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The authors concludes that they are impervious to advice, which is the reason of the tone behind the paragraph.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> In time past in Nigeria, being a secretary was perceived with utter disdain by many people. Other professionals such as teachers, lawyers, engineers, surveyors, estate officers and architects were revered. Many issues readily come to mind concerning the old perspective of secretaries as professionals. <br/>  <br/> One, they were regarded as people with little or no education, indeed, many of them were said to be mere typist who learnt how to punch keys on the typewriters. They hardly had any formal education but obtain doubtful certificates. This was made possible because anyone could easily learn to be as typist under the shade tree or in a personal office of a retired secretary or a chief typist from any business organization. As long as a short piece of work could be typed almost accurately and in record time, one then became a secretary. This unrealistic practice - to call an unqualified person a secretary - might have been introduced and sustained by people who did not know who a secretary was. The education secretaries obtained a minimum of Ordinary Notional Diploma (OND) or its equivalent from institutions in and outside Nigeria, particularly Great Britain, Canada or the United State of America. <br/>  <br/> Two, they were mostly women and very few males secretaries, who suffered more humiliation than their female counterparts. They were regards as men who did not succeed in life and did the work that normally women were supposed to do.  <br/>  <br/> Three, and derived from the second reason, secretaries were, as a matter of fact, very close to their bosses. Most people, including husband of secretaries, regarded such a mode of interaction as tempting - a kind of constant closeness which might engender a deliberate or unintentional amorous relationship between superior and subordinate officers. Quite often, such a situation could not be ruled out when body contact was established inadvertently or deliberately between two people of opposite sex especially when either one or both people were attracted to each other. Moreover, we often talk of the devil and the havoc he is capable of causing in lives of people, particularly the unguarded ones. <br/>  <br/> In today worlds these points of view concerning secretaries are fading fast. Now, there is a clear distinction between typist and a secretary. Modern secretaries are trained in polytechnics and universities. Gone are the days when secretaries were taught only the art of punching the typewriters and various filling systems. They are also encouraged to take training courses other than secretarial duty. Many secretaries have had their training in faculties of business administration, law, arts and mass communication of universities. They take relevant courses in administration and other social science department that enhance their personality, carriage, interpersonal relations and office management. Obviously, secretaries, including the male ones, are more important and well respected today than in the past. <br/>  <br/> The writer seems to suggest that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">secretaries were best trained by retired chief typists </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there was nothing wrong in having males as secretaries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Ordinary National Diploma was sufficient for secretaries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">only graduates who studied abroad were secretaries</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The writer suggests that there was nothing wrong in having males as secretaries. This is evident in the passage where the writer states that 'Obviously, secretaries, including the male ones, are more important and well respected today than in the past.' This implies that the writer believes that the gender of the secretary does not determine their ability or value in their role.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> In time past in Nigeria, being a secretary was perceived with utter disdain by many people. Other professionals such as teachers, lawyers, engineers, surveyors, estate officers and architects were revered. Many issues readily come to mind concerning the old perspective of secretaries as professionals. <br/>  <br/> One, they were regarded as people with little or no education, indeed, many of them were said to be mere typist who learnt how to punch keys on the typewriters. They hardly had any formal education but obtain doubtful certificates. This was made possible because anyone could easily learn to be as typist under the shade tree or in a personal office of a retired secretary or a chief typist from any business organization. As long as a short piece of work could be typed almost accurately and in record time, one then became a secretary. This unrealistic practice - to call an unqualified person a secretary - might have been introduced and sustained by people who did not know who a secretary was. The education secretaries obtained a minimum of Ordinary Notional Diploma (OND) or its equivalent from institutions in and outside Nigeria, particularly Great Britain, Canada or the United State of America. <br/>  <br/> Two, they were mostly women and very few males secretaries, who suffered more humiliation than their female counterparts. They were regards as men who did not succeed in life and did the work that normally women were supposed to do.  <br/>  <br/> Three, and derived from the second reason, secretaries were, as a matter of fact, very close to their bosses. Most people, including husband of secretaries, regarded such a mode of interaction as tempting - a kind of constant closeness which might engender a deliberate or unintentional amorous relationship between superior and subordinate officers. Quite often, such a situation could not be ruled out when body contact was established inadvertently or deliberately between two people of opposite sex especially when either one or both people were attracted to each other. Moreover, we often talk of the devil and the havoc he is capable of causing in lives of people, particularly the unguarded ones. <br/>  <br/> In today worlds these points of view concerning secretaries are fading fast. Now, there is a clear distinction between typist and a secretary. Modern secretaries are trained in polytechnics and universities. Gone are the days when secretaries were taught only the art of punching the typewriters and various filling systems. They are also encouraged to take training courses other than secretarial duty. Many secretaries have had their training in faculties of business administration, law, arts and mass communication of universities. They take relevant courses in administration and other social science department that enhance their personality, carriage, interpersonal relations and office management. Obviously, secretaries, including the male ones, are more important and well respected today than in the past. <br/> Modern secretaries are different from the old ones because they </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are able to become graduates of various universities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">may become teachers in polytechnics and universities </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are more educated and better exposed to professional training </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">can use modern gadgets such as computers and other machines</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Modern secretaries are different from the old ones because they are more educated and better exposed to professional training. This is evident in the passage where the writer states that 'Modern secretaries are trained in polytechnics and universities. They are also encouraged to take training courses other than secretarial duty. Many secretaries have had their training in faculties of business administration, law, arts and mass communication of universities.' This shows that modern secretaries have a broader and more comprehensive education and training compared to the old ones.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> In time past in Nigeria, being a secretary was perceived with utter disdain by many people. Other professionals such as teachers, lawyers, engineers, surveyors, estate officers and architects were revered. Many issues readily come to mind concerning the old perspective of secretaries as professionals. <br/>  <br/> One, they were regarded as people with little or no education, indeed, many of them were said to be mere typist who learnt how to punch keys on the typewriters. They hardly had any formal education but obtain doubtful certificates. This was made possible because anyone could easily learn to be as typist under the shade tree or in a personal office of a retired secretary or a chief typist from any business organization. As long as a short piece of work could be typed almost accurately and in record time, one then became a secretary. This unrealistic practice - to call an unqualified person a secretary - might have been introduced and sustained by people who did not know who a secretary was. The education secretaries obtained a minimum of Ordinary Notional Diploma (OND) or its equivalent from institutions in and outside Nigeria, particularly Great Britain, Canada or the United State of America. <br/>  <br/> Two, they were mostly women and very few males secretaries, who suffered more humiliation than their female counterparts. They were regards as men who did not succeed in life and did the work that normally women were supposed to do.  <br/>  <br/> Three, and derived from the second reason, secretaries were, as a matter of fact, very close to their bosses. Most people, including husband of secretaries, regarded such a mode of interaction as tempting - a kind of constant closeness which might engender a deliberate or unintentional amorous relationship between superior and subordinate officers. Quite often, such a situation could not be ruled out when body contact was established inadvertently or deliberately between two people of opposite sex especially when either one or both people were attracted to each other. Moreover, we often talk of the devil and the havoc he is capable of causing in lives of people, particularly the unguarded ones. <br/>  <br/> In today worlds these points of view concerning secretaries are fading fast. Now, there is a clear distinction between typist and a secretary. Modern secretaries are trained in polytechnics and universities. Gone are the days when secretaries were taught only the art of punching the typewriters and various filling systems. They are also encouraged to take training courses other than secretarial duty. Many secretaries have had their training in faculties of business administration, law, arts and mass communication of universities. They take relevant courses in administration and other social science department that enhance their personality, carriage, interpersonal relations and office management. Obviously, secretaries, including the male ones, are more important and well respected today than in the past. <br/> The expression <em>utter disdain</em>, as used in the passage means </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">professional misconduct</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">undue criticism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deserved respect </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">complete contempt</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'utter disdain' as used in the passage refers to the complete contempt or lack of respect that was shown towards secretaries in the past. This is evident from the context in which the phrase is used in the passage. The phrase 'utter disdain' is used to describe the negative perception and lack of respect for the profession of secretaries in the past. Therefore, the correct option is 'complete contempt'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> In time past in Nigeria, being a secretary was perceived with utter disdain by many people. Other professionals such as teachers, lawyers, engineers, surveyors, estate officers and architects were revered. Many issues readily come to mind concerning the old perspective of secretaries as professionals. <br/>  <br/> One, they were regarded as people with little or no education, indeed, many of them were said to be mere typist who learnt how to punch keys on the typewriters. They hardly had any formal education but obtain doubtful certificates. This was made possible because anyone could easily learn to be as typist under the shade tree or in a personal office of a retired secretary or a chief typist from any business organization. As long as a short piece of work could be typed almost accurately and in record time, one then became a secretary. This unrealistic practice - to call an unqualified person a secretary - might have been introduced and sustained by people who did not know who a secretary was. The education secretaries obtained a minimum of Ordinary Notional Diploma (OND) or its equivalent from institutions in and outside Nigeria, particularly Great Britain, Canada or the United State of America. <br/>  <br/> Two, they were mostly women and very few males secretaries, who suffered more humiliation than their female counterparts. They were regards as men who did not succeed in life and did the work that normally women were supposed to do.  <br/>  <br/> Three, and derived from the second reason, secretaries were, as a matter of fact, very close to their bosses. Most people, including husband of secretaries, regarded such a mode of interaction as tempting - a kind of constant closeness which might engender a deliberate or unintentional amorous relationship between superior and subordinate officers. Quite often, such a situation could not be ruled out when body contact was established inadvertently or deliberately between two people of opposite sex especially when either one or both people were attracted to each other. Moreover, we often talk of the devil and the havoc he is capable of causing in lives of people, particularly the unguarded ones. <br/>  <br/> In today worlds these points of view concerning secretaries are fading fast. Now, there is a clear distinction between typist and a secretary. Modern secretaries are trained in polytechnics and universities. Gone are the days when secretaries were taught only the art of punching the typewriters and various filling systems. They are also encouraged to take training courses other than secretarial duty. Many secretaries have had their training in faculties of business administration, law, arts and mass communication of universities. They take relevant courses in administration and other social science department that enhance their personality, carriage, interpersonal relations and office management. Obviously, secretaries, including the male ones, are more important and well respected today than in the past. <br/> The expression <em>unguarded ones</em>, as used in the passage, refers to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the devil and all his cohorts </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">husbands of female secretaries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">two people who may be attracted to each other </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the female secretaries and their bosses </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'unguarded ones' as used in the passage refers to people who may be vulnerable to inappropriate behavior or situations due to their close proximity or attraction to each other. This is evident from the context in which the phrase is used in the passage. The phrase 'unguarded ones' is used to describe people who may be susceptible to the 'devil and the havoc he is capable of causing' due to their close interaction and potential attraction to each other. Therefore, the correct option is 'two people who may be attracted to each other'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> In time past in Nigeria, being a secretary was perceived with utter disdain by many people. Other professionals such as teachers, lawyers, engineers, surveyors, estate officers and architects were revered. Many issues readily come to mind concerning the old perspective of secretaries as professionals. <br/>  <br/> One, they were regarded as people with little or no education, indeed, many of them were said to be mere typist who learnt how to punch keys on the typewriters. They hardly had any formal education but obtain doubtful certificates. This was made possible because anyone could easily learn to be as typist under the shade tree or in a personal office of a retired secretary or a chief typist from any business organization. As long as a short piece of work could be typed almost accurately and in record time, one then became a secretary. This unrealistic practice - to call an unqualified person a secretary - might have been introduced and sustained by people who did not know who a secretary was. The education secretaries obtained a minimum of Ordinary Notional Diploma (OND) or its equivalent from institutions in and outside Nigeria, particularly Great Britain, Canada or the United State of America. <br/>  <br/> Two, they were mostly women and very few males secretaries, who suffered more humiliation than their female counterparts. They were regards as men who did not succeed in life and did the work that normally women were supposed to do.  <br/>  <br/> Three, and derived from the second reason, secretaries were, as a matter of fact, very close to their bosses. Most people, including husband of secretaries, regarded such a mode of interaction as tempting - a kind of constant closeness which might engender a deliberate or unintentional amorous relationship between superior and subordinate officers. Quite often, such a situation could not be ruled out when body contact was established inadvertently or deliberately between two people of opposite sex especially when either one or both people were attracted to each other. Moreover, we often talk of the devil and the havoc he is capable of causing in lives of people, particularly the unguarded ones. <br/>  <br/> In today worlds these points of view concerning secretaries are fading fast. Now, there is a clear distinction between typist and a secretary. Modern secretaries are trained in polytechnics and universities. Gone are the days when secretaries were taught only the art of punching the typewriters and various filling systems. They are also encouraged to take training courses other than secretarial duty. Many secretaries have had their training in faculties of business administration, law, arts and mass communication of universities. They take relevant courses in administration and other social science department that enhance their personality, carriage, interpersonal relations and office management. Obviously, secretaries, including the male ones, are more important and well respected today than in the past. <br/> Which of the following statements can be deduced from the passage concerning the old perspective of secretaries?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They did not deserve to be addressed as secretaries </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One could see that they were well educated </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They were highly respected by other professionals </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The training they received from retired professionals was sufficient </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the passage, it is clear that secretaries in the past were not given the respect and recognition they deserved. They were often seen as uneducated individuals who merely learned to type. This is why option 1, 'They did not deserve to be addressed as secretaries', is the correct answer. The passage does not suggest that they were well educated, highly respected by other professionals, or that their training from retired professionals was sufficient, which makes the other options incorrect.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> While trying desperately to cope with the scourge of the dreaded HIV/AIDS l, the virus, the human race was once again beset with the problem of grappling with another fast-spreading and lethal pandemic called bird flu. Also called avian influenza, Bird flu vicious strain, H5NI was spread from birds to human and could also be as HIV/AIDS. The pandemic had ravaged many countries in Europe, Asia and Middle East, resulting in a high death toll in livestock, but as yet with a few human casualties. <br/>  <br/> As the pandemic made its steady spread there was the fear that, if it ever got to Africa, the consequence would be devastating in view of the continent's lack of infrastructure and money to keep it in control. This fear was consequent upon Africa countries unenviable response to emergences in the past, like drought in some shelling countries or flooding along the coast. It was against this frightening background that many Nigerians were thrown into panic following the announcement on Wednesday the 18th of February, 2006, that the bird flu had indeed entered Nigeria.  <br/>  <br/> The announcement itself was sequel to death of a large number of birds in a farm in Kaduna states whose sample were diagnosed at the National Veterinary Institute, Vom, Plateau State, and confirmed at the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) diagnostic center in Rome, Italy. Several follow-up actions had been taken to try and halt the spread of the virus in the country, such as the immediate quarantine of the affected farms, the killing and disposal of all infected and surviving birds in affected farms and the restriction of movement of people in and outside such farms, commendable as these measure were, many Nigerian still dreaded the chicken and had already excluded its meat from their menu. As a result, poultry farmers in Nigeria were counting their losses instead of producing more protein and smiling to the bank with good sales.  <br/>  <br/> To return to the <em>state quo ante</em> and restore the confidence of Nigeria in poultry products, additional measures were suggested, namely the close monitoring of migratory  birds which flock into the country at different time of the years, the proper caging of all free-range birds and appropriate sanctioning of defaulting owners, not restricting the monitoring of poultry farms in the country to the urban centers only, the upward review of the  compensation paid to farmers whose birds had been destroyed to cushion the effect of their loss, the strict enforcement of the restriction on the importation of poultry products and, lastly, the leadership demonstrating, by example, that it was safe to eat poultry products by several them at dinners and banquets during state functions. <br/>  <br/> From the third paragraph, the steps taken to check the spread of bird flu in Nigeria were </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monitoring all poultry farms, quarantining affected farms and killing and disposing of affected birds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">restricting movement, paying compensation and caging free-range birds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">isolating ravaged farms, destroying and disposing of affected birds and restricting movement</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">public enlightenment, controlling migratory birds and killing infested birds</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage mentions that the steps taken to check the spread of bird flu in Nigeria included the immediate quarantine of the affected farms, the killing and disposal of all infected and surviving birds in affected farms, and the restriction of movement of people in and outside such farms. Therefore, option 3, 'isolating ravaged farms, destroying and disposing of affected birds and restricting movement', is the correct answer. The other options mention measures that were suggested but not necessarily implemented, according to the passage.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> While trying desperately to cope with the scourge of the dreaded HIV/AIDS l, the virus, the human race was once again beset with the problem of grappling with another fast-spreading and lethal pandemic called bird flu. Also called avian influenza, Bird flu vicious strain, H5NI was spread from birds to human and could also be as HIV/AIDS. The pandemic had ravaged many countries in Europe, Asia and Middle East, resulting in a high death toll in livestock, but as yet with a few human casualties. <br/>  <br/> As the pandemic made its steady spread there was the fear that, if it ever got to Africa, the consequence would be devastating in view of the continent's lack of infrastructure and money to keep it in control. This fear was consequent upon Africa countries unenviable response to emergences in the past, like drought in some shelling countries or flooding along the coast. It was against this frightening background that many Nigerians were thrown into panic following the announcement on Wednesday the 18th of February, 2006, that the bird flu had indeed entered Nigeria.  <br/>  <br/> The announcement itself was sequel to death of a large number of birds in a farm in Kaduna states whose sample were diagnosed at the National Veterinary Institute, Vom, Plateau State, and confirmed at the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) diagnostic center in Rome, Italy. Several follow-up actions had been taken to try and halt the spread of the virus in the country, such as the immediate quarantine of the affected farms, the killing and disposal of all infected and surviving birds in affected farms and the restriction of movement of people in and outside such farms, commendable as these measure were, many Nigerian still dreaded the chicken and had already excluded its meat from their menu. As a result, poultry farmers in Nigeria were counting their losses instead of producing more protein and smiling to the bank with good sales.  <br/>  <br/> To return to the <em>state quo ante</em> and restore the confidence of Nigeria in poultry products, additional measures were suggested, namely the close monitoring of migratory  birds which flock into the country at different time of the years, the proper caging of all free-range birds and appropriate sanctioning of defaulting owners, not restricting the monitoring of poultry farms in the country to the urban centers only, the upward review of the  compensation paid to farmers whose birds had been destroyed to cushion the effect of their loss, the strict enforcement of the restriction on the importation of poultry products and, lastly, the leadership demonstrating, by example, that it was safe to eat poultry products by several them at dinners and banquets during state functions. <br/> Which of the following statements is true according to the passage?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's handling of the bird flu pandemic justified African countries' inability to cope with the disaster</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If it had not been quickly controlled, bird flu might have proved more deadly than HIV/AIDS</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The death of many poultry birds led to the discovery of bird flu in Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Poultry farms in Nigeria had been quarantined</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"The death of many poultry birds led to the discovery of bird flu in Nigeria\". This can be seen in the 3rd paragraph.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> While trying desperately to cope with the scourge of the dreaded HIV/AIDS l, the virus, the human race was once again beset with the problem of grappling with another fast-spreading and lethal pandemic called bird flu. Also called avian influenza, Bird flu vicious strain, H5NI was spread from birds to human and could also be as HIV/AIDS. The pandemic had ravaged many countries in Europe, Asia and Middle East, resulting in a high death toll in livestock, but as yet with a few human casualties. <br/>  <br/> As the pandemic made its steady spread there was the fear that, if it ever got to Africa, the consequence would be devastating in view of the continent's lack of infrastructure and money to keep it in control. This fear was consequent upon Africa countries unenviable response to emergences in the past, like drought in some shelling countries or flooding along the coast. It was against this frightening background that many Nigerians were thrown into panic following the announcement on Wednesday the 18th of February, 2006, that the bird flu had indeed entered Nigeria.  <br/>  <br/> The announcement itself was sequel to death of a large number of birds in a farm in Kaduna states whose sample were diagnosed at the National Veterinary Institute, Vom, Plateau State, and confirmed at the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) diagnostic center in Rome, Italy. Several follow-up actions had been taken to try and halt the spread of the virus in the country, such as the immediate quarantine of the affected farms, the killing and disposal of all infected and surviving birds in affected farms and the restriction of movement of people in and outside such farms, commendable as these measure were, many Nigerian still dreaded the chicken and had already excluded its meat from their menu. As a result, poultry farmers in Nigeria were counting their losses instead of producing more protein and smiling to the bank with good sales.  <br/>  <br/> To return to the <em>state quo ante</em> and restore the confidence of Nigeria in poultry products, additional measures were suggested, namely the close monitoring of migratory  birds which flock into the country at different time of the years, the proper caging of all free-range birds and appropriate sanctioning of defaulting owners, not restricting the monitoring of poultry farms in the country to the urban centers only, the upward review of the  compensation paid to farmers whose birds had been destroyed to cushion the effect of their loss, the strict enforcement of the restriction on the importation of poultry products and, lastly, the leadership demonstrating, by example, that it was safe to eat poultry products by several them at dinners and banquets during state functions. <br/> From the passage, it can be inferred that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigerians no longer consumed poultry products as a result of bird flu</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bird flu had already resulted in a high human and livestock death toll</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bird flu in Nigeria was first discovered by the Food and Agriculture Organization(FAO) Diagnostic Centre</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Kaduna poultry farmer who lost many birds was not adequately compensated by government </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage mentions that many Nigerians still dreaded the chicken and had already excluded its meat from their menu due to the bird flu. This implies that Nigerians no longer consumed poultry products as a result of bird flu.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> While trying desperately to cope with the scourge of the dreaded HIV/AIDS l, the virus, the human race was once again beset with the problem of grappling with another fast-spreading and lethal pandemic called bird flu. Also called avian influenza, Bird flu vicious strain, H5NI was spread from birds to human and could also be as HIV/AIDS. The pandemic had ravaged many countries in Europe, Asia and Middle East, resulting in a high death toll in livestock, but as yet with a few human casualties. <br/>  <br/> As the pandemic made its steady spread there was the fear that, if it ever got to Africa, the consequence would be devastating in view of the continent's lack of infrastructure and money to keep it in control. This fear was consequent upon Africa countries unenviable response to emergences in the past, like drought in some shelling countries or flooding along the coast. It was against this frightening background that many Nigerians were thrown into panic following the announcement on Wednesday the 18th of February, 2006, that the bird flu had indeed entered Nigeria.  <br/>  <br/> The announcement itself was sequel to death of a large number of birds in a farm in Kaduna states whose sample were diagnosed at the National Veterinary Institute, Vom, Plateau State, and confirmed at the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) diagnostic center in Rome, Italy. Several follow-up actions had been taken to try and halt the spread of the virus in the country, such as the immediate quarantine of the affected farms, the killing and disposal of all infected and surviving birds in affected farms and the restriction of movement of people in and outside such farms, commendable as these measure were, many Nigerian still dreaded the chicken and had already excluded its meat from their menu. As a result, poultry farmers in Nigeria were counting their losses instead of producing more protein and smiling to the bank with good sales.  <br/>  <br/> To return to the <em>state quo ante</em> and restore the confidence of Nigeria in poultry products, additional measures were suggested, namely the close monitoring of migratory  birds which flock into the country at different time of the years, the proper caging of all free-range birds and appropriate sanctioning of defaulting owners, not restricting the monitoring of poultry farms in the country to the urban centers only, the upward review of the  compensation paid to farmers whose birds had been destroyed to cushion the effect of their loss, the strict enforcement of the restriction on the importation of poultry products and, lastly, the leadership demonstrating, by example, that it was safe to eat poultry products by several them at dinners and banquets during state functions. <br/> The expression <em>To return to the status quo ante </em> refers to the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">killing of birds as a result of bird flu and its effects on poultry farmers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bird flu pandemic that had ravaged many countries in Europe, Asia and the Middle East </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">condition of things prior to the incidence of bird flu</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">state of affairs following the bird flu pandemic in Nigeria</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'To return to the status quo ante' is a Latin phrase that means 'to return to the state of affairs as it was before'. In the context of the passage, it refers to the condition of things prior to the incidence of bird flu, particularly the confidence of Nigerians in poultry products.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the question that follows.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> While trying desperately to cope with the scourge of the dreaded HIV/AIDS l, the virus, the human race was once again beset with the problem of grappling with another fast-spreading and lethal pandemic called bird flu. Also called avian influenza, Bird flu vicious strain, H5NI was spread from birds to human and could also be as HIV/AIDS. The pandemic had ravaged many countries in Europe, Asia and Middle East, resulting in a high death toll in livestock, but as yet with a few human casualties. <br/>  <br/> As the pandemic made its steady spread there was the fear that, if it ever got to Africa, the consequence would be devastating in view of the continent's lack of infrastructure and money to keep it in control. This fear was consequent upon Africa countries unenviable response to emergences in the past, like drought in some shelling countries or flooding along the coast. It was against this frightening background that many Nigerians were thrown into panic following the announcement on Wednesday the 18th of February, 2006, that the bird flu had indeed entered Nigeria.  <br/>  <br/> The announcement itself was sequel to death of a large number of birds in a farm in Kaduna states whose sample were diagnosed at the National Veterinary Institute, Vom, Plateau State, and confirmed at the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) diagnostic center in Rome, Italy. Several follow-up actions had been taken to try and halt the spread of the virus in the country, such as the immediate quarantine of the affected farms, the killing and disposal of all infected and surviving birds in affected farms and the restriction of movement of people in and outside such farms, commendable as these measure were, many Nigerian still dreaded the chicken and had already excluded its meat from their menu. As a result, poultry farmers in Nigeria were counting their losses instead of producing more protein and smiling to the bank with good sales.  <br/>  <br/> To return to the <em>state quo ante</em> and restore the confidence of Nigeria in poultry products, additional measures were suggested, namely the close monitoring of migratory  birds which flock into the country at different time of the years, the proper caging of all free-range birds and appropriate sanctioning of defaulting owners, not restricting the monitoring of poultry farms in the country to the urban centers only, the upward review of the  compensation paid to farmers whose birds had been destroyed to cushion the effect of their loss, the strict enforcement of the restriction on the importation of poultry products and, lastly, the leadership demonstrating, by example, that it was safe to eat poultry products by several them at dinners and banquets during state functions. <br/> A suitable title for this passage is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Livestock and Human Casualties of the Bird Flu Pandemic in Nigeria </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Controlling the Bird Flu Pandemic in Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">HIV/AIDS and the Bird Flu Pandemic in Nigeria </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Ravaging Effects of Epidemics in Nigeria</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage discusses the bird flu pandemic in Nigeria, its effects, and the measures taken to control it. Therefore, the most suitable title for this passage is 'Controlling the Bird Flu Pandemic in Nigeria'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/>  <br/> ...1...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lied </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lay </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lain</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">laid</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'laid'. In the context of the sentence, the correct past participle of the verb 'to lay' (meaning to put or set down) should be used. The sentence implies that the people have not set their eyes on the king for a long time, hence 'laid' is the appropriate word to use.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...2...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were gathered </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gather </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to be gathering</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gathers</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'were gathered'. In the context of the sentence, the past continuous tense should be used to indicate that the action (people gathering in the palace arena) was ongoing at a certain time in the past (the morning of the Ofala). Therefore, 'were gathered' is the appropriate phrase to use.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...3...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">booms</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">shoots</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">knocks</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bangs</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the cannon is described as making a loud, resonating noise, which is best described by the word 'booms'. A cannon doesn't 'knock' or 'shoot', and while it can 'bang', 'boom' is a more specific and appropriate term for the sound a cannon makes.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...4...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vibration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gyration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">explosion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">percussion</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the word that best describes the sound coming from the royal musician is 'percussion'. This is because percussion refers to musical instruments that make a sound when they are hit, shaken, or scraped. The other options, 'vibration', 'gyration', and 'explosion', do not accurately describe the type of sound that would come from a musician.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...5...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">royally</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resplendent </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dazzled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">surrounded</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"resplendent\" best suits. <br/> adjective: resplendent <br/>  <br/>     attractive and impressive through being richly colourful or sumptuous. <br/>     \"she was resplendent in a sea-green dress\"</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...6...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">traditional </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">social </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">royal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cultural</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'traditional' is the most appropriate to fill the gap in the sentence. It refers to something that is a part of the customs and ways of doing things that have been used by the people in a particular group, family, society, etc., for a long time. The Ofala festival is a traditional event in the Igbo community. The other options do not fit as well. 'Social' refers to relating to society or its organization, 'royal' refers to relating to a king or queen, and 'cultural' refers to the ideas, customs, and social behavior of a society. However, in the context of the sentence, 'traditional' is the most fitting.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...7...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">from the cheers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at the cheer</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">with the cheers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to the cheers</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'from the cheers' is the most appropriate to fill the gap. This is because the Igwe is dancing round the arena to the cheers and praises of the crowd. The preposition 'from' is used to indicate the source or origin of something, in this case, the cheers of the crowd. The other options do not fit contextually into the sentence.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...8...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pay their respects</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spray him with gifts</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">observe his steps</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pay their tolls</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'pay their respects' is the most appropriate to fill the gap. This is because the context of the passage suggests that the people are showing reverence to the Igwe by declaring 'Igweeee! You will live long'. The other options do not fit contextually into the sentence.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...9...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at the throne</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">on the throne</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by the throne</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in the throne </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'on the throne'. This is because the preposition 'on' is used to indicate position for surfaces or a position just above or outside an area. Therefore, when referring to the position of the king, we say he is 'on the throne' not 'at', 'by', or 'in' the throne.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">The passage below has gaps numbered 1 to 10. Immediately following each gap, four options are provided. <br/>  Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>   <br/>  PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> Ofala is a festival that is celebrated in virtually every Igbo community in Nigeria. It is the king's own festival during which he shows himself to his people, many of whom have probably not ...1... eyes on him for a long time. The morning of the Ofala sees large crowds ...2... in the palace arena. Suddenly a cannon ...3... repeatedly. Rich ...4.... from the royals musician fills the air. The Igwe emerges like the rising sun ...5... in white-bordered gold and black robes. The Igwe then begins the ...6... dance with his wife. Followed by his entourage, he dance round the arena ...7...and praises of the crowd. Finally, the Igwe takes his seat and his people begins to ...8... \"Igweeee!\" You will live long ...9... they declare, bowing respectfully before the him. The Igwe ...10...  their homage by touching their back with his royal fly whisk. Exhausted, the Igwe rises \"igweeee\", the crowd hails, he waves his fly whisk for the last time and heads straight back to the palace with his entourage. <br/> ...10...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">answers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">responds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">acknowledges</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">replies</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct word is 'acknowledges'. This is because in the context of the passage, the Igwe is recognizing or expressing recognition of the people's homage. This is best described by the word 'acknowledge'. The other options 'answers', 'responds', and 'replies' suggest a verbal or written reaction, which is not the case here.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p> <br/>  <br/> He <em>deprecated</em> the attempts made to unseat him.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">despised </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">challenged</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resisted </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">condemned</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'deprecated' means to express disapproval of something. In this context, it means that he expressed disapproval of the attempts made to unseat him. The option that is nearest in meaning to 'deprecated' is 'condemned', which means to express complete disapproval of something.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The striking workers have vowed not to return to work until the decision is <em>reversed </em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rescinded </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">implemented</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dismissed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reverted</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'reversed' in this context means to change a decision, rule, or process so that it is the opposite of what it was before. The option that is nearest in meaning to 'reversed' is 'rescinded', which means to revoke, cancel, or repeal a law, order, or agreement.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The police are not happy with the growing number of <em>depraved</em> people around the politician.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">violent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">immoral</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indolent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loquacious</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'depraved' is used to describe someone who is morally corrupt or wicked. Therefore, the option 'immoral' is the nearest in meaning to 'depraved'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The last criticism at the rally was <em>made in ignorance</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">uninformed </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unimpeachable</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">objective</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">impeccable</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'made in ignorance' means that something was done without knowledge or awareness. Therefore, the option 'uninformed' is the nearest in meaning to 'made in ignorance'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The astute businessman neatly <em>fended off </em> questions about his private life.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">asked </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">explained</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">welcomed </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sidestepped </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'fended off' in this context means to avoid or evade something. In this case, the businessman is avoiding questions about his private life. Therefore, the option nearest in meaning is 'sidestepped'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> We were warned not to indulge in <em>recriminations</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">counter-charges</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">accusations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indiscretions </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">frivolous allegations</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'recriminations' refers to an accusation in response to one from someone else. It's a retaliatory action where one party accuses the other in return. Therefore, the option nearest in meaning is 'counter-charges'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The shortage of petrol was a <em>perennial problem</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a recurring</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an annual</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a seasonal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an incurable</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'perennial' in the context of the question refers to something that is enduring or continually recurring. Therefore, the option 'a recurring' is the closest in meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The rest of the boys admire Olu's <em>verve</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">intelligence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">handsomeness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">work</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">energy</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'verve' refers to the spirit and enthusiasm animating artistic composition or performance. Therefore, the option 'energy' is the closest in meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> He holds on firmly to his <em>hackneyed</em> view of life.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wayward </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">principled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obsolete</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">positive </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'hackneyed' means something that is overused to the point of being worn out or commonplace. In this context, it refers to a view of life that is outdated or no longer relevant. Therefore, the option 'obsolete' which means outdated or no longer in use, is the closest in meaning to 'hackneyed'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> I visited Amina <em>umpteen times</em> in her college, but she never came to me.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">often </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seldom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">twice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">occasionally</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'umpteen times' is an informal way of saying 'many times' or 'often'. Therefore, the option 'often' is the closest in meaning to 'umpteen times'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The debt the company incurred became rather <em>intolerable</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inevitable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unprecedented</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">insupportable</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dangerous</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'intolerable' means something that is unbearable or insupportable. Therefore, the option that is nearest in meaning to 'intolerable' is 'insupportable'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The tax rebate was a <em>concession</em> given to the civil servants.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a donation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an allowance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an incentive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an emolument</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A 'concession' is a kind of allowance or benefit given to someone. Therefore, the option that is nearest in meaning to 'concession' is 'an allowance'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> <em>Beads</em> of sweat ran down Ngozi's armpit.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pools</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Springs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ponds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rivulets</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'beads' in this context refers to small droplets of sweat. The closest meaning to this among the options is 'rivulets', which refers to a small stream, and can metaphorically be used to describe a small flow or trickle of a liquid, such as sweat.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The noise across the road <em>drowned</em> the sound of the keyboard in my room.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">neutralized </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">overshadowed </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">balanced </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equalized </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'drowned' in this context means to make a sound inaudible or obscure by being much louder. The closest meaning to this among the options is 'overshadowed', which means to make something seem less important or less happy by comparison.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>nearest in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Things may change soon, but at the moment our economic situation is <em>precarious</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">redeemable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">buoyant </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">uncertain </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unattractive </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'precarious' means not securely held or in position; dangerously likely to fall or collapse. In the context of the economic situation, it means that the situation is unstable or uncertain. Therefore, the option 'uncertain' is the nearest in meaning to 'precarious'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>same consonant sound </em>as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p> <br/>  <br/> Shoe<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">s</span></div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">horse</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">house</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loss</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reason</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reason and shoes both have the same consonant sound /z/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>same consonant sound </em>as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> E<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">n</span>glish</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">end</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">thin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">think</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">edge</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"English\" and \"think\" both have the consonant /ŋ/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>same consonant sound </em>as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Clo<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">th</span>e </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thomas</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">three</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mouth (n.)</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">clothe and they both have the consonant sound /ð/. Thomas has /t/ while the others have /θ/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>same vowel sound </em>as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p> <br/>  <br/> P<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">o</span>table </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">paw</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pot </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">port</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">post</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Potable and post both have the vowel sound /əʊ/. This is the accurate answer <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>same vowel sound </em>as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Bl<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ue</span></div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">book</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">root</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">foot</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">look</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Both blue and root have the vowel sound /u:/ while the others have the short variant.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>same vowel sound </em>as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> P<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ea</span>r</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dear</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">year</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">near</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Both pear and there have the vowel sound /eə/ while the rest have /ɪə/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p> <br/>  <br/> The refugees were received at the <em>transit</em> camp.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">passage </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">permanent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">temporary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nearby</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'transit' refers to the act or process of moving from one place to another. It is often used to describe a temporary or short-term state. Therefore, the opposite of 'transit' in this context would be 'permanent', which refers to something that lasts or remains unchanged indefinitely.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The man paid a large sum to <em>redeem</em> his mortgaged property.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ransom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">acquire</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pawn </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recover</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'redeem' in this context means to regain possession of something in exchange for payment. The opposite of this would be to give up possession of something in exchange for payment, which is what 'pawn' means.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Lami and her husband are simply <em>munificent</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wealthy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">angry</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">happy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">niggardly</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'munificent' means very generous. The opposite of being generous is being stingy or ungenerous, which is what 'niggardly' means.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> 'Is it necessary for us to go?' she asked in her <em>shrill</em> voice.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">angry</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">quiet</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indistinct </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">aggressive</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'shrill' refers to a voice or sound that is high-pitched and piercing. The opposite of a shrill voice would be an indistinct voice, which is not clearly or sharply defined.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>51", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The police demanded a <em>factual</em> account of the accident.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a supportive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an uncorroborated</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an admissible</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an undisguised</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'factual' refers to something that is based on facts. The opposite of a factual account would be an uncorroborated account, which is not confirmed or supported by evidence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>52", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The suggestions he made were very <em>unobtrusive</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forceful</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">helpful</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sincere</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reasonable</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'unobtrusive' means not conspicuous or attracting attention. The opposite of this would be something that is forceful or attracting attention. Therefore, the correct answer is 'forceful'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>53", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Mr. Adeyemo is quite a <em>conceited</em> young man.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a resourceful</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an experienced </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a practical </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an unassuming</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'conceited' means excessively proud of oneself or vain. The opposite of this would be someone who is modest or unassuming. Therefore, the correct answer is 'an unassuming'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>54", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The stadium was <em>seething</em> with people when we entered. </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">filled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">crowded </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">empty</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">noisy</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'seething' in this context means to be filled or overflowing with a large amount of something, in this case, people. Therefore, the opposite of 'seething' would be 'empty'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>55", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The Vice-Chancellor <em>relinquished</em> power at the end of his term.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abandoned </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wielded </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gave up</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">clung on to </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'relinquished' means to voluntarily cease to keep or claim; to give up. Therefore, the opposite of 'relinquished' would be 'clung on to' which means to hold on tightly to.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>56", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The students were <em>undeterred</em> by the noisy lecture environment.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">frustrated </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encouraged</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discouraged</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">challenged</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'undeterred' means not discouraged or prevented from doing something. Therefore, the opposite of 'undeterred' is 'discouraged'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>57", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> For anything to do with academic work, he has to have a great <em>aversion</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">conversion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">attention</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">contempt</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">predilection</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An aversion is a strong dislike. The opposite word will be predilection; which means a preference or special liking for something; a bias in favour of something.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>58", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The study he carried out of the problem was quite <em>comprehensive</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">detailed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sketchy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inscrutable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">complete</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'comprehensive' means complete or covering all aspects of something. The opposite of 'comprehensive' would be something that is incomplete or only covers a few aspects. In the given options, 'sketchy' is the word that best fits this description. 'Sketchy' means not thorough or detailed, which is the opposite of 'comprehensive'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>59", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The man advised his  wife to <em>steer a middle course</em> in the argument between her and her employers.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be recalcitrant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be unrepentant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be compromising</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be unrelenting</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'steer a middle course' means to adopt a moderate or balanced position, especially in a dispute. The opposite of this would be to adopt an extreme or uncompromising position. In the given options, 'be unrelenting' is the phrase that best fits this description. 'Be unrelenting' means to be inflexible or uncompromising, which is the opposite of 'steer a middle course'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>60", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Do not be <em>discouraged</em> by failure in life.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">overjoyed </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dissuaded </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">actuated</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disoriented</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To be discouraged is to be disoriented; having lost confidence or enthusiasm; disheartened. The opposite word is actuated; motivated.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>61", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option <em>opposite in meaning</em> to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Otokpa took after his late father who was a <em>teetotaller</em>. </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a drunk </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">careless</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a disciplinarian</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sober</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Teetotalism is the practice or promotion of complete personal abstinence from alcoholic beverages. Drunkenness is the opposite word.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>62", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Choose the appropriate stress pattern from the options. The syllables are written in capital letters.*! <br/>  <br/> capitalism</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">capiTAlism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">capitaLism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">caPItalism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">CApitalism</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">CApitalism. This is the accurate stress pattern for the word. <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>63", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/>  <br/>  Choose the appropriate stress pattern from the options. The syllables are written in capital letters.*!  <br/>  <br/> association</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">aSSOciation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">associaTION</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">associAtion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Association</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">associAtion. This is the accurate stress pattern for the word.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>64", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/>  <br/>  Choose the appropriate stress pattern from the options. The syllables are written in capital letters.*!  <br/>  <br/> advertisement </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adVERtisement</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">advertiseMENT</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adverTISEment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ADvertisement</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In English pronunciation, the stress in the word 'advertisement' falls on the second syllable, making the correct pronunciation 'adVERtisement'.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>65", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>stress on the first syllable</em>.</p> <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">intact</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">integral</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">negotiate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">about</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">INtegral. This is the accurate stress pattern for the word.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>66", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>stress on the first syllable</em>.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">conduce</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">renewal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">calender</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reproduce</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">CAlender. This is the accurate stress pattern for the word.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>67", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has the <em>stress on the first syllable</em>.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">understand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">address</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">afternoon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taxi</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the word 'taxi', the stress is on the first syllable 'tax-'.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>68", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has a <em>different stress pattern</em> from the others.</p> <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">superior</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">surcharge</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">slaughter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">superman</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suPErior is stressed on the second syllable while the others are stressed on the first syllable.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>69", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has a <em>different stress pattern</em> from the others.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">education</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">individual</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">agriculture</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cinderella</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Only Agriculture is stressed on the first syllable.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>70", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that has a <em>different stress pattern</em> from the others.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cigarette</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">European</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">evacuate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taxi</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In English, stress pattern refers to the emphasis placed on certain syllables in words. 'Cigarette', 'European', and 'evacuate' all have stress on the second syllable, while 'taxi' has stress on the first syllable. Therefore, 'taxi' has a different stress pattern from the others.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>71", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> Because of his ....... nature, Ayo was tricked out of his wristwatch.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">kind</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pliable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">uncompromising </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">uncalculating </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In this context, 'pliable' means easily influenced or controlled by others. The sentence implies that Ayo was tricked because of his easily influenced nature, so 'pliable' is the word that best completes the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>72", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> He says he ....... find me a job, but will accomodate me.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">could not </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was not able to </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is not able to </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cannot be able to </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'was not able to'. The sentence is in the past tense, indicated by 'says' and 'will'. Therefore, the verb that fills the gap should also be in the past tense. 'Was not able to' is the only option that fits this criteria.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>73", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The idle steward could not see ....... on the wall, and he lost his job.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the writing </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">what will be written</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the handwriting </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">what is written</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'the writing'. The phrase 'the writing on the wall' is an idiomatic expression that means a sign or warning of impending disaster. The steward's inability to see 'the writing on the wall' suggests that he failed to recognize the signs that he was about to lose his job.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>74", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> ...... went to the stadium to watch a football match.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amadi and me</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amadi and I</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Me and Amadi</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amadi and myself</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Amadi and I\" is most appropriate. <strong>I</strong> is the first person singular subject pronoun , which means that it refers to the person performing the action of a verb.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>75", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> If he arrived late, everyone ...... him.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">would have blamed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">will blame </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">would blame </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">must blame</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'everyone would blame him'. This is a second conditional sentence, which is used to talk about things which are unlikely to happen or hypothetical situations. The structure is 'if + past simple, ...would + infinitive'. So, 'would blame' is the correct form to use in this context.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>76", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> When they examined his body, they found that he ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had been dead</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had been dying</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">died</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was dead</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'was dead'. The sentence is in the past tense and is describing a state (being dead) at a specific time in the past (when they examined his body). 'Had been dead' and 'had been dying' are past perfect continuous and past perfect tenses respectively, which are used to show that an action started in the past and continued up until another time in the past. 'Died' is simple past tense which indicates an action completed at a specific time in the past. However, the sentence requires a state (not an action) at a specific time in the past, hence 'was dead' is the correct answer.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>77", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The rain fell for days ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">on ending</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at ending</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">on end </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at end</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'on end'. The phrase 'for days on end' is an idiom that means 'for many days in a row'. 'On ending' and 'at ending' are not standard English phrases, and 'at end' is not the correct idiom.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>78", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Yesterday in the hall, Ola said that ...... his watch.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he had mislaid</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he had forgot</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he had misplaced</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he have lost</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to use in this context is 'he had mislaid'. 'Mislaid' means to put something in a place where it cannot readily be found and forgotten where it is. This is the most appropriate term to use when referring to something like a watch that has been lost in this manner. The other options are grammatically incorrect or do not fit the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>79", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Government should invest more in ...... training.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">teacher's</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">teacher</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">teachers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">teachers'</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to use in this context is 'teachers' training'. This is because the training is for multiple teachers, not just one, so the plural form 'teachers' is used. The apostrophe after 'teachers' indicates possession, showing that the training belongs to the teachers. The other options are grammatically incorrect or do not fit the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>80", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The team has benefitted from the coach's ...... of experience.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">minefield</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reservoir</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wealth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">world</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'wealth of experience'. This phrase is used to describe a large amount of experience that someone has. The word 'wealth' in this context means 'an abundance or a large quantity of something'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>81", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> There was ...... any traffic as he drove home.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hardly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">normally</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">usually</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">no</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'hardly any traffic'. This phrase is used to describe a situation where there is very little traffic. The word 'hardly' in this context is used to mean 'almost not'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>82", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> I look forward to ...... you next week.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seen</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seeing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be seeing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">see</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"seeing\" is most appropriate. When \"to\" is used as a preposition, it should be succeeded by a noun or nominal element, e.g. gerund (verb+ing).</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>83", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The girl cannot speak with a clear voice, she is always ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">blabbing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vociferating </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spluttering</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gesticulating</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct word to use in this context is 'spluttering'. 'Spluttering' means to speak quickly and in a way that is not clear, often because of strong emotion. This fits the context of the sentence, which implies that the girl cannot speak clearly. The other options do not fit the context. 'Blabbing' means to reveal secrets by talking carelessly or thoughtlessly. 'Vociferating' means to shout, complain, or argue loudly or vehemently, which does not necessarily imply a lack of clarity. 'Gesticulating' means to use gestures, especially dramatic ones, instead of speaking or to emphasize one's words, which is not related to the clarity of speech.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>84", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The politician ...... the family of the deceased.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">greeted </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">condoled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wept over</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commiserated with </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to use when expressing sympathy for someone's death is 'commiserate with'. This means to express sympathy or condolences. Therefore, the politician 'commiserated with' the family of the deceased.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>85", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Making a phone call instead of paying a visit represents a ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sudden new major social</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">new social sudden major</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">new sudden major social </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sudden social new major</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This follows the order of adjectives. This is the accurate answer <br/> </div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>86", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Our soldiers are starting to zero ...... the enemy.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in on</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unto</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">on at </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'zero in on'. It is an idiomatic expression that means to focus one's attention on something or someone. Therefore, the correct option is 'in on'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>87", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> My father has been away on a journey but my mother says she ...... he ...... this Friday.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expects/would arrive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expected/will arrive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expects/will arrive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expected/ would arrive</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'expects/will arrive'. In this context, 'expects' is used because the mother is currently expecting the father to arrive. 'Will arrive' is used to express a future event that is certain or sure to happen. Therefore, the correct option is 'expects/will arrive'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>88", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Kola was fined, ...... thieves were given a jail sentence.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the rest of the </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the rest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rest of the </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"the rest of the\" is most appropriate. This best complete the sentence. </div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>89", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> I ...... to pursue my education.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not chance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not have the opportunity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was not chanced</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was not opportuned</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to complete the sentence is 'did not have the opportunity'. The sentence implies that the speaker was unable to pursue their education. The phrase 'did not have the opportunity' is used to express the lack of chance or possibility to do something.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>90", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the option that <em>best completes</em> the gap.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Didn't ...... draw your attention to the entry requirements?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">anyone</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">everyone </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">everybody</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nobody</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'anyone'. In the context of the sentence, the speaker is asking if there was any single person who drew attention to the entry requirements. 'Anyone' is used to refer to any person or people. The other options 'everyone', 'everybody', and 'nobody' do not fit in the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>91", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p> <br/>  <br/> He could not have rewarded them more handsomely.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He did not reward them very well</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He rewarded them well, and he was also a good looking man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He rewarded them very well </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He spoke to them in a very generous way</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'He rewarded them very well'. The phrase 'could not have rewarded them more handsomely' is an idiomatic expression that means he rewarded them very well or generously. The other options do not accurately convey the meaning of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>92", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> My advice to Tolu was: 'Look before you leap.'</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tolu was advised to consider her opinions before reaching any decisions</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tolu was advised to consider the possible consequences before taking action</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tolu was advised to weigh her decisions by looking and leaping</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tolu was advised to leap only after looking</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'Look before you leap' is a proverb that means one should think carefully about the possible results or consequences before doing something or making a decision. Therefore, the sentence implies that Tolu was advised to consider the possible consequences before taking action.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>93", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The official had allegedly been taking bribes.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Some people accused the official of taking bribes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The official had been taking bribes without feeling any guilt</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It was proved that the official had been taking bribes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The official accused  some  people of taking bribes</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To allege is to claim or assert that someone has done something illegal or wrong, typically without proof.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>94", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Emeka hardly ever holds with my view on good governance.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Emeka sometimes opposes my idea of good governance </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">My view on what good governance is conforms with that Emeka</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Emeka never really supports my opinion of good governance </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Emeka may never hold a view which conflicts with mine on good governance </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'hardly ever holds with' means 'rarely agrees with'. Therefore, the sentence implies that Emeka rarely agrees with the speaker's view on good governance. The option 'Emeka never really supports my opinion of good governance' best captures this meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>95", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The next village is at least 30 kilometres away.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The next village is 30 kilometres away, possibly less</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The next village is approximately 30 kilometres away</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The next village is only 30 kilometres away</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The next village is 30 kilometres away, or possibly more</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'at least' means 'not less than' or 'more than or equal to'. Therefore, the sentence implies that the next village is not less than 30 kilometres away, or it could be more. The option 'The next village is 30 kilometres away, or possibly more' best captures this meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>96", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The woman won't have lived through the night.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It was likely that the woman died before morning </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The woman survived her ordeal but not without some help</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From all indications, the woman was taken much worse,though she overcame her ordeal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The woman might not have lived if she hadn't got the right support</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'won't have lived through the night' implies that the woman is not expected to survive until morning. This is a future perfect tense structure, which is used to talk about actions that are expected to be completed by a certain point in the future. In this case, the action is the woman's survival, and the point in the future is 'the night'. The expectation is negative (won't have lived), indicating that she is expected to die before morning. Therefore, the option 'It was likely that the woman died before morning' best explains the information conveyed in the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>97", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> There's a door at either end of the building.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The building has two ends and two doors</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The building has two end, but only one door</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The building has two two ends, but I do not know which of the two has a door</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The building has many ends, each with a door</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'There's a door at either end of the building' implies that the building has two ends and there is a door at each end. The word 'either' is used to refer to one or the other of two things. In this case, it refers to the two ends of the building. Therefore, the option 'The building has two ends and two doors' best explains the information conveyed in the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>98", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> We have to iron out our differences at once.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We must clear up without delay our misunderstanding </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We must ensure that our problems are eliminated at all costs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We have to settle our disagreement once and for all</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We have to solve some of our problems for now</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'iron out our differences' is an idiomatic expression that means to resolve or settle disputes, disagreements or misunderstandings. Therefore, the sentence 'We have to iron out our differences at once' means that the misunderstandings or disagreements need to be cleared up without delay. Option 1 'We must clear up without delay our misunderstanding' correctly interprets this meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>99", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> There should be a level playing field for women entering politics.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Women should not be allowed to enter politics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sports facilities should be provided for women entering politics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Special privileges should be given to women who want to enter politics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Men and women should be able to compete in the political arena on an equal basis</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'level playing field' is an idiomatic expression that means a situation in which everyone has a fair and equal chance of succeeding. Therefore, the sentence 'There should be a level playing field for women entering politics' means that women should have the same opportunities and chances as men in politics. Option 4 'Men and women should be able to compete in the political arena on an equal basis' correctly interprets this meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2007>100", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Select the option that <em>best explains</em> the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The country is holding its first free elections since five years.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The last time the country held free elections was five years ago</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The first free elections in the country have now taken five years to conduct</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The country held elections five years ago but they were not free</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">There were elections in the country five years ago </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sentence 'The country is holding its first free elections since five years' implies that the last time the country held free elections was five years ago. The use of 'since' in this context indicates the time that has passed since the last occurrence of an event, in this case, the free elections.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}];
